blocks.text:
The **main factors affecting a length measurement** are:
- **temperature** (thermal expansion and distortion);
- **force** (elastic deformation, Hooke's law);
- the **shape** of the measurement surfaces and of the measurand (their interaction).

In addition, two **typical measurement errors** appear: the **zero error** (a constant $A$) and the **sensitivity error** (proportional to length, factor $B$), giving the binomial deviation $A+B\cdot L$.

**Force effects** follow Hooke's law. Normal forces give small axial elongations; **bending moments** give large shape changes. A gauge block standing on its lower face shortens under its own weight by $\Delta L=-\rho g L^2/(2E)$ — proportional to $L^2$ — so ISO requires blocks **$\le 100$ mm** to be calibrated in **vertical** position (compression negligible) and blocks **$>100$ mm** in **horizontal** position. A horizontal block is supported on **two points**:
- **Airy points** $a=L/\sqrt{12}=0.2887\,L$ make the **end rotations null** (faces stay parallel) — used when length is between end faces;
- **Bessel points** $a=0.2779\,L$ **minimise the deflection** — used when length is not associated with the end faces.
